# Testing PXE Content

The PXE content image includes built-in tests so the image can be validated without moving test scripts to a VM, cloning the project, or using real PXE hardware.

## Recommended test command

Use the `:test` image tag when validating a merge request or branch build:

```bash
podman run --rm \
  --entrypoint /usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test \
  registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com/lit/containers/pxe-content:test \
  all
```

A successful run ends with all tests passing.

This is the preferred quick proof that the image is healthy before merging.

## What the built-in tests prove

The test runner validates that the image can:

- start in a test container
- find Python, Nginx, and the generator script
- compile the generator script
- create fake RHEL ISO trees for testing
- detect valid ISO trees
- ignore incomplete ISO trees
- generate `boot.ipxe`
- generate Kickstart files
- generate `index.html`
- generate `status.json`, `status.txt`, and `isos.txt`
- serve content over HTTP using Nginx
- render Jinja Kickstart templates and partials
- apply override profiles and override templates
- preserve manual `/ks` edits by default
- overwrite manual `/ks` edits when configured
- report validation errors in warn mode
- fail on validation errors in fail mode
- avoid leaking the root password hash into status and index files
- keep placeholder profiles from creating real boot targets

These tests do not prove that a physical machine can PXE boot on a specific network. They prove the image-generated HTTP content is structurally healthy and internally consistent.

## Test runner

The image installs this test runner:

```text
/usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test
```

The source file is:

```text
tests/pxe-content-test
```

The test runner calls the project test scripts under:

```text
/usr/local/share/aerolit-pxe-content/tests/
```

## Test scripts

| Script | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `test-basic-image.sh` | Validates basic generator behavior, generated files, fake ISO detection, Kickstart content, status health, and HTTP serving |
| `test-overrides-and-preserve-policy.sh` | Validates override profiles, override templates, Jinja partial rendering, manual `/ks` edit preservation, and overwrite behavior |
| `test-validation-health-policy.sh` | Validates status health, validation reporting, warn policy, fail policy, and validation error handling |
| `test-lib.sh` | Shared helper functions used by the test scripts |
| `pxe-content-test` | Convenience wrapper for running the tests from inside the image |

## Running all tests

```bash
podman run --rm \
  --entrypoint /usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test \
  registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com/lit/containers/pxe-content:test \
  all
```

## Running tests from a live container

If the image is already running as `pxe-content`, you can run tests with:

```bash
podman exec pxe-content /usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test all
```

The test runner creates its own temporary test paths under `/tmp`, so it does not need real ISO content.

## Running individual scripts from source

When working from a local clone of the project, the scripts can also be run directly:

```bash
./tests/test-basic-image.sh
./tests/test-overrides-and-preserve-policy.sh
./tests/test-validation-health-policy.sh
```

By default, the scripts target a running container named:

```text
pxe-content
```

Override the container name with:

```bash
CID=<container-name> ./tests/test-basic-image.sh
```

## Image tag expectations

Recommended tag usage:

| Tag | Intended use |
|---|---|
| `test` | Easy manual testing of the latest merge request or branch build |
| `sha-<commit>` | Commit-specific traceability |
| `mr-<number>` | Merge-request-specific traceability, if enabled |
| `latest` | Default branch / promoted image after merge |

For normal MR validation, use:

```text
pxe-content:test
```

For promoted usage after merge, use:

```text
pxe-content:latest
```

## Testing without PXE hardware

The tests do not require DHCP, TFTP, iPXE clients, Foreman, or a physical machine.

The basic image test creates fake ISO content like this:

```text
/tmp/pxe-basic/iso/rhel8iso/images/pxeboot/vmlinuz
/tmp/pxe-basic/iso/rhel8iso/images/pxeboot/initrd.img
/tmp/pxe-basic/iso/rhel8iso/BaseOS/repodata/repomd.xml
/tmp/pxe-basic/iso/rhel8iso/AppStream/repodata/repomd.xml
```

It then generates PXE content and starts a temporary Nginx instance to confirm that the generated HTTP paths can be served.

This catches most image, generator, template, and content regressions before testing with real PXE hardware.

## What to check before merging

Before merging a PXE content change, run:

```bash
podman run --rm \
  --entrypoint /usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test \
  registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com/lit/containers/pxe-content:test \
  all
```

The merge request is in good shape when:

- the image builds successfully
- the `:test` tag is pushed
- the built-in test command passes
- the generated status output reports healthy content
- no expected profile, template, or generated file is missing

## Common test failures

### `No such file or directory`

Confirm the test runner exists inside the image:

```bash
podman run --rm \
  --entrypoint /bin/sh \
  registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com/lit/containers/pxe-content:test \
  -lc 'ls -l /usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test /usr/local/share/aerolit-pxe-content/tests/'
```

### `Permission denied`

Confirm the Dockerfile makes the test scripts executable.

Expected installed paths:

```text
/usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test
/usr/local/share/aerolit-pxe-content/tests/*.sh
```

### HTTP 404 during tests

This usually means the temporary Nginx test root cannot serve the generated path.

Check:

- the generated file exists
- the fake ISO tree was linked under the generated web root
- Nginx is using the expected test config
- the test root has usable directory permissions

### Jinja include or partial errors

This usually means an override template references a partial path that is not available to the Jinja loader.

Use built-in partial names from:

```text
templates/partials/
```

Example include:

```jinja
{% include "partials/packages-minimal.ks.j2" %}
```

### Validation fail policy did not fail

Confirm the test intentionally created broken generated content and ran with:

```text
PXE_VALIDATION_FAILURE_POLICY=fail
```

The generator should still write status files before exiting non-zero.
